1. Plain Logit

Estimation Procedure

  • The indirect utility function, assuming no heterogeneity, is given by \[ u_{ijm} = \bar{\beta}_0 + x_{j} \bar{\beta}_1 + \xi_{jm} + \varepsilon_{ijm}. \]
  • Define the mean utility: \[ \delta_j = \bar{\beta}_0 + x_{j}' \bar{\beta}_1 + \xi_{jm} \]
    • Then, \(u_{ijm} = \delta_{j} + \varepsilon_{ijm}\).
  • As we have seen in the class, the market share (or, choice probability) is given by \[ s_{jm}(\delta) = \frac{\exp(\delta_{jm})}{1 + \sum_{k=1}^J\exp(\delta_{km})} \]
    • \(\delta_0\) is normalized to \(0\).
  • By Berry inversion, we have \[ \log(s_{jm}) - \log(s_{0m}) = \delta_{jm} \]

Estimation

  • Compute share and \(\delta\).
mkt_size = 100000    # market size is 100,000 by assumption

df_market <- df_market %>% 
  bind_rows(outside) %>% 
  arrange(market, product) %>% 
  group_by(market) %>% 
  mutate(total_inside = sum(quantity, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(quantity = if_else(product == 0, mkt_size - total_inside , quantity)) %>% 
  mutate(share = quantity / mkt_size) %>%
  mutate(delta_plain = log(share / share[1])) %>% 
  ungroup()

df_market
  • Estimate the regression.
reg_result <- lm(delta_plain ~ characteristics, data = df_market, subset = (product != 0))

2. BLP approach

Estimation Procedure

  • The indirect utility function is \[ \begin{align} u_{ijm} & =\bar{\beta}_{0}+x_{j}\cdot\left(\bar{\beta}_{1}+\beta_{1}^{u}\nu_{i1m}\right)+\xi_{jm}+\varepsilon_{ijm}\\ & =\left(\bar{\beta}_{0}+x_{j}\bar{\beta}_{1}+\xi_{jm}\right)+x_{j}\beta_{1}^{u}\nu_{i1m}+\varepsilon_{ijm}\\ & =\delta_{jm}+\mu_{ijm}+\varepsilon_{ijm}. \end{align} \]

  • First, we simulate consumer-level heterogeneity, \(\nu_{v1m}\).

  • Let \(\theta = \beta_1^u\).

  • Using the simulated data and some initial \(\delta_{jm}\), we compute the simulated share by: \[ \hat{s}_{jm}(\delta, \theta)=\frac{1}{ns}\sum_{i=1}^{ns}\left[\frac{\exp(\delta_{jm}+\mu_{ijm}(\theta))}{1+\sum_{j'=1}^{10}\exp(\delta_{j'm}+\mu_{ij'm}(\theta))}\right] \]

    • By contraction mapping, we can obtain \(\delta_{jm}^*(\theta)\).

  • With \(\delta_{jm}^*\) at hand, we estimate fixed effect FE model to obtain \((\bar{\beta}_0,\bar{\beta}_1)\) and \(\xi_{jm}^*(\theta)\):

\[ \delta_{jm}^{*}(\theta) = \bar{\beta}_{0}+x_{j}\bar{\beta}_{1}+\xi_{jm} \]

  • Notice that the above procedure solely depends on \(\theta\).
    • Namely, if we provide the value of \(\theta\), then we get all the folloing parameters, which depends on \(\theta\):
      • \(\delta, \xi, \bar{\beta}_{0}, \bar{\beta}_{1}\)
    • Since economic theory (or assumption) suggests that there is no endogeneity, a natural way to estimate \(\theta\) is minimizing the squared sums of \(\xi_{jm}(\theta)\).
  • Minimize the objective function \(\xi^{\ast \top}\xi^*\).

Estimation

  • Parameters we want to estimate: \(\theta = \beta_1^u\).
    • As descrived above, \((\bar{\beta}_0,\bar{\beta}_1)\) is automatically estimated if \(\theta\) is given.
# initial value of theta
theta = c(1)
  • Consumer-level heterogeneity
num_sim <- 1000    # number of simulations
M <- length(market)    # number of markets

df_individual <- tibble(
  id = rep(1:num_sim, times = M),
  market = rep(market, each = num_sim),
  nu_1 = rnorm(M * num_sim)
)

  • Using this \(\delta\), we regress \(\delta_{jm}\) on \((1,x)\) to get \(\xi_{jm}^*\).
    • The function return the squared sum of \(xi\).
HW3_compute_xi_squared(theta, delta_init, df_simulated, df_market, tolerance)
[1] 452.1345
  • Now, we minimize \(xi\) to get the parameter \(\theta\).
    • The results are robust to several initial parameters:
theta_init <- c(0, 1, 10)
theta_opt <- numeric(3)

for(i in seq_along(theta_init)){
  optim_result <- optim(theta_init[i], HW3_compute_xi_squared, delta_init = delta_init, df_simulated = df_simulated, df_market = df_market, tolerance = 1e-05, method = 'Brent', lower = -5, upper = 15)
  theta_opt[i] <- optim_result$par
}

optim_result_df <- tibble(
  initial_value = c("0", "1", "10"),
  theta = theta_opt
)
optim_result_df
  • Use the optimal \(\theta\) to get linear parameters.
theta_optim <- optim_result$par
par_linear <- HW3_compute_linear_params(theta_opt, delta_opt, df_simulated, df_market)
par_linear

  • In sum, we get the following estimation result by plain logit and BLP:

\[ \begin{align*} \text{plain logit}:\qquad & u_{ijm}=-2.80 + 1.12 x_{j}+\xi_{jm}+\varepsilon_{ijm}\\ \text{BLP}:\qquad & u_{ijm}= -0.69 +x_{j}\cdot\left(-0.90 + 4.21 \nu_{i1m}\right)+\xi_{jm}+\varepsilon_{ijm} \end{align*} \]
